WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.720
Hi, I'm George, I'm a software engineer at Posit, and today I'm going to talk to you

00:00:04.720 --> 00:00:08.480
about reproducible data science with webR and Shinylive.

00:00:08.480 --> 00:00:12.400
Before I actually get into the webR and the Shinylive stuff, I do want to talk a little

00:00:12.400 --> 00:00:15.960
bit about reproducible data science, so that's where I'll start.

00:00:15.960 --> 00:00:21.280
One of the really important principles of the scientific method in general is the idea

00:00:21.280 --> 00:00:26.160
of peer review and verification, the idea that when you do some kind of analysis or

00:00:26.400 --> 00:00:32.720
scientific work, you can take that work, give it to someone else, and they can redo what you

00:00:32.720 --> 00:00:37.919
did based on your data and come to the same conclusions. With this, we can verify each

00:00:37.919 --> 00:00:40.639
other's work, and that makes really good science.

00:00:40.639 --> 00:00:47.200
And because of this reason, researchers are increasingly publishing their data, as well

00:00:47.200 --> 00:00:51.759
as the infrastructure and their source code for software that they use to build their

00:00:51.759 --> 00:00:56.799
analyses. In fact, in some places, this is actually becoming an institutional or regulatory

00:00:56.799 --> 00:01:03.200
requirement. In some universities, for example, you may be given funding and told, okay, well,

00:01:03.200 --> 00:01:07.360
any outputs you produce from this funding must be open access, so anyone can download

00:01:07.360 --> 00:01:08.480
those results.

00:01:08.480 --> 00:01:13.599
Or if you're in a regulatory environment like healthcare or pharma, governments may say

00:01:13.599 --> 00:01:18.400
to you, okay, well, you have to make your outputs accessible to everyone. And I think

00:01:18.400 --> 00:01:23.919
that makes sense when you have something like a government, that their outputs should

00:01:23.919 --> 00:01:26.800
be viewable by the people who are under that government.

00:01:26.800 --> 00:01:31.760
So this idea of open science is, there's a whole bunch of sections that's shown in this

00:01:31.760 --> 00:01:36.639
little diagram here, and you can read more about it at the links on the screen. But really

00:01:36.639 --> 00:01:42.480
what I'm going to talk about is the idea of this open research data and open software.

00:01:42.480 --> 00:01:46.400
And the people who care about this kind of thing, they're taking inspiration and lessons

00:01:46.720 --> 00:01:51.120
from the world of free and open source software, which has been around for maybe 40 or 50 years

00:01:51.120 --> 00:01:56.879
now. All those ideas of free and open source software can be applied to the idea of open

00:01:56.879 --> 00:01:58.080
scientific knowledge.

00:01:58.080 --> 00:02:03.599
And this takes us to reproducibility, the idea that if you have some kind of data analysis,

00:02:04.239 --> 00:02:10.320
it should be created in such a way that other researchers can come to the same conclusions

00:02:10.320 --> 00:02:10.800
as you.

00:02:10.800 --> 00:02:17.839
Now that's nice in principle, but in practice, things don't go so nicely. There was a paper

00:02:17.839 --> 00:02:26.320
published in 2022 that took a bunch of research outputs, ones that involved R code, and they

00:02:26.320 --> 00:02:32.080
take the look at the data in the R code and they try to rerun those analyses.

00:02:32.960 --> 00:02:39.199
And unfortunately, what they found was that 74% of R files included with open research

00:02:39.199 --> 00:02:43.679
failed to run on the first try. They would error or some other problem would occur.

00:02:44.800 --> 00:02:48.639
And I remember a colleague of mine, Winston, showed me this paper, and I remember being

00:02:48.639 --> 00:02:54.800
really quite disappointed when I saw it. I'm a former academic myself, and I remember thinking

00:02:54.800 --> 00:03:04.479
that surely we can do better than that. Who are we to say that we find truth when 74% of R code

00:03:04.479 --> 00:03:08.080
fails to run? It was really quite upsetting.

00:03:08.080 --> 00:03:12.479
This is really important, this idea that when we write code, it should be runnable anywhere.

00:03:13.039 --> 00:03:21.520
And for some research codes, like for some research projects, these trials may be going

00:03:21.520 --> 00:03:25.839
on for years. So it's good that any code that we do write should be able to run in the same

00:03:25.839 --> 00:03:32.960
way for years to come. So what do I mean when I say the word reproducible? Now, there's no real

00:03:33.440 --> 00:03:39.119
hard definition for when a piece of software is reproducible or a piece of analysis is reproducible.

00:03:40.080 --> 00:03:46.000
There's just many guidelines. One definition that I like is that something's reproducible

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:51.039
if anyone can go and rerun and verify the result of some computational procedure.

00:03:52.639 --> 00:03:58.880
As a follow-on to that, you also get the ability to modify or extend that procedure.

00:03:59.679 --> 00:04:05.440
Perhaps you go and collect more data, or perhaps there is extended software that you've written or

00:04:05.440 --> 00:04:11.360
you can use to extend that piece of work and gain new insights. Now, you'll notice with that

00:04:11.360 --> 00:04:18.320
definition that there's a level of subjectivity, there's a word easily in there. And what's easy

00:04:18.320 --> 00:04:24.559
for some people is not going to be easy for other people. I'm a software engineer and I might find

00:04:24.559 --> 00:04:30.239
quite technical things very easy, while a working researcher may not have that knowledge and

00:04:30.239 --> 00:04:36.480
experience of really working deep with technical software or procedures. And they might find

00:04:37.040 --> 00:04:43.440
certain reproducibility methods more difficult to handle. And because of that, there are these levels

00:04:43.440 --> 00:04:49.679
of reproducibility where some things are quite easily done that can make your software run in

00:04:49.679 --> 00:04:56.480
more places, while there are really deep technical ways to ensure that you have a

00:04:56.480 --> 00:05:05.279
reproducible environment everywhere that are much harder to do. There are resources to

00:05:05.279 --> 00:05:10.559
help you with this. Building reproducible analytical pipelines with R is a good starter for anyone who

00:05:10.559 --> 00:05:17.679
is wanting to build these reproducible processes in R itself. And there's also the

00:05:17.760 --> 00:05:24.480
carpentries. These are really, really great people. They'll go into institutions like

00:05:24.480 --> 00:05:30.959
universities and they'll teach good software engineering and teach how to make

00:05:30.959 --> 00:05:36.559
software that's reproducible and high quality. What I'm going to do is I'm going to start from a

00:05:36.559 --> 00:05:42.320
very light touch, first level of reproducibility to tell you what that looks like.

00:05:42.959 --> 00:05:47.519
And then I'll sort of get more into the weeds about where these things can kind of go wrong

00:05:47.519 --> 00:05:54.559
and sort of more technical ways to ensure that your software will run for years to come.

00:05:55.600 --> 00:06:00.880
And then once I've talked about that, I'll talk about one of the methods of reproducibility with

00:06:00.880 --> 00:06:07.119
Shiny. And that's Shiny Live and WebAssembly. And that'll be at the end. So the first step,

00:06:07.679 --> 00:06:13.200
if you really want to make sure that your code is reproducible is realize that there's

00:06:13.200 --> 00:06:17.600
no guarantee that any script that you run will run successfully anywhere else.

00:06:19.119 --> 00:06:24.160
What you're trying to avoid is the also common, it works on my machine. That's kind of

00:06:25.040 --> 00:06:30.320
the first hump that you have to get over is that mindset. You'll find that the things you have to

00:06:30.320 --> 00:06:36.799
do to get started here aren't too difficult. It's stuff that we probably all as R or Python

00:06:36.799 --> 00:06:42.640
programmers should be doing anyway. It's basically just paying attention to where your

00:06:42.640 --> 00:06:49.040
working directory is, where your files are stored and what data sets are required to run your script

00:06:49.040 --> 00:06:53.200
and where they live on disk. Bearing in mind, if you have multiple scripts, what order should

00:06:53.200 --> 00:06:58.239
you run those scripts in? And just sort of avoiding programming errors, just making sure

00:06:58.239 --> 00:07:03.200
that if you run your script from top to bottom, it runs without any errors. And like I say,

00:07:03.200 --> 00:07:08.320
anyone can do these things. They're not technically difficult, they're just sort of

00:07:08.320 --> 00:07:15.839
paying attention to what you're doing. And even this small effort makes a big difference. In the

00:07:15.839 --> 00:07:20.880
study I talked about earlier, they found that when they applied these very simple sort of checks

00:07:20.880 --> 00:07:27.839
onto the R code, it went from 74% failing to just 56% failing. And that is a big jump for

00:07:27.839 --> 00:07:33.279
stuff that we should all be doing anyway. The next level, once you've written a piece of code,

00:07:33.279 --> 00:07:37.200
it's a good solid piece of code, you're checking for errors, you've made sure you know where your

00:07:37.200 --> 00:07:42.799
scripts live, is sort of what I called at the language level. And now we're starting to talk

00:07:42.799 --> 00:07:49.040
about just sort of good software engineering. The idea of making sure that your code is kept

00:07:49.040 --> 00:07:55.920
in something like Git for source code management, programming defensively. So if something could

00:07:56.000 --> 00:08:03.200
fail, checking for such a failure condition and handling that. And also things like organizing

00:08:03.200 --> 00:08:08.559
your software into modules or packages and avoiding things like deprecated functionality

00:08:08.559 --> 00:08:15.200
if you're using packages. And most importantly, at least in my opinion, documentation and tests,

00:08:15.200 --> 00:08:18.239
really making sure that your software is doing what you think it's doing.

00:08:18.959 --> 00:08:24.799
Now this stuff's a little bit harder, but there are packages to help you do this. There's a bunch

00:08:24.799 --> 00:08:28.640
of packages in R that I've shown on the screen there that can help you with this sort of

00:08:28.640 --> 00:08:34.080
language level software engineering. And I'm sure there are similar packages in Python,

00:08:34.080 --> 00:08:40.400
but really there's no magic bullet. It is just sort of making sure that somebody on your team

00:08:40.400 --> 00:08:46.159
who is writing software has those good software engineering skills. And again,

00:08:46.159 --> 00:08:53.520
there are sort of societies and groups to make this better. So the Society of Research Software

00:08:53.520 --> 00:08:59.039
Engineering is a society that's certainly been up and coming in the UK universities over the last

00:08:59.039 --> 00:09:06.719
few years. And there is a US version as well. And what they will do is they'll go into places like

00:09:06.719 --> 00:09:11.919
universities and they're really advocating for this kind of work, this good software engineering

00:09:11.919 --> 00:09:17.359
in research. And they're really trying to push for the idea that a research software engineer

00:09:17.359 --> 00:09:24.400
should be a valid career path for someone who is doing kind of research and wants to

00:09:24.400 --> 00:09:31.760
make sure that the research software is open and high quality. Okay, so even if you've

00:09:32.640 --> 00:09:37.679
done all of that, at some point you'll probably take your code and you'll want to run it somewhere

00:09:37.679 --> 00:09:44.000
else. The example I use in sort of the academic setting is if you have some kind of data analysis

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:48.159
and you want to send it to someone for peer review. This kind of thing happens in science

00:09:48.159 --> 00:09:55.520
all of the time. Now, unfortunately, if you do have software, everyone's computational environment is

00:09:55.520 --> 00:09:59.280
going to be slightly different. They're going to have different versions of software or packages

00:09:59.280 --> 00:10:06.400
installed, for example. Here on the left, I've shown some examples of real situations I've seen

00:10:06.400 --> 00:10:11.039
where different versions of certain packages have caused problems with somebody's code running on

00:10:11.039 --> 00:10:17.200
someone else's machine, whether it's a version of R or Python. And also I saw a case once where

00:10:17.200 --> 00:10:21.520
the version of Node caused a problem, which is a JavaScript engine. But even so, even if you have

00:10:21.520 --> 00:10:26.400
the same version of R installed on a machine, you might have different packages. And again,

00:10:26.400 --> 00:10:33.119
there are tools to help with this. Rig and pyenv are R and Python tools respectively for

00:10:33.119 --> 00:10:40.159
managing the versions of R and Python on your machine. And renv and venv are packages that

00:10:40.159 --> 00:10:45.599
will manage the versions of packages for your projects for, again, R and Python. They can kind

00:10:45.599 --> 00:10:50.559
of take a snapshot of the versions of packages installed in your machine and reproduce that

00:10:50.559 --> 00:10:54.400
environment on somebody else's machine so that you know they've got the same versions of the

00:10:54.400 --> 00:10:58.799
packages on their machine. So when they run your code, it's going to give the same answer.

00:10:58.799 --> 00:11:05.039
In addition to that, I've also added p3m here, which is the sort of short name for Posit Package

00:11:05.039 --> 00:11:10.000
Manager. And I do want to shout this out specifically because this is a great tool for

00:11:11.280 --> 00:11:18.400
building reproducible R scripts and Python scripts. Because what it is, is it's a version

00:11:18.400 --> 00:11:22.960
of the CRAN and PyPy package managers that you can actually, if you go into the setup

00:11:23.599 --> 00:11:31.840
and run through the options, you can actually pick a specific date in time.

00:11:32.799 --> 00:11:38.960
And if you set that up as your package repository in R or Python, what you'll find is that the

00:11:38.960 --> 00:11:43.760
versions of the packages from the repository will be at that point in time. So you know that if you

00:11:43.760 --> 00:11:50.000
come back to a project in a year's time, if you use this repository and select the date that

00:11:50.880 --> 00:11:55.919
project was written, those packages installed will be exactly the same versions. So that's

00:11:55.919 --> 00:12:01.599
really, really useful if you're trying to freeze a point in time for your particular project.

00:12:01.599 --> 00:12:06.400
Saying that, even if you have the same versions of packages installed, again, there's another

00:12:06.400 --> 00:12:14.239
layer, which is sort of system libraries. A lot of packages and software itself like R will actually

00:12:14.239 --> 00:12:18.960
call out to system software. And you can have different versions of system software installed

00:12:18.960 --> 00:12:23.440
on machines. So you could have different implementations of Blas and Lepak, for example,

00:12:24.080 --> 00:12:29.840
depending on whether you're running a Linux machine or Windows machine. And in those cases,

00:12:29.840 --> 00:12:35.200
you can get slight differences in results because of that. What you'll notice is as I'm going sort

00:12:35.200 --> 00:12:42.000
of deeper into the layers, you'll find that you get closer and closer to full reproducibility.

00:12:43.280 --> 00:12:49.840
We're reaching the point now with system libraries where you might find small variations in results,

00:12:49.840 --> 00:12:53.119
but generally the overall result should be pretty much the same by this point.

00:12:53.919 --> 00:12:58.239
However, if you find that it really is important that a certain system library has to be the same

00:12:58.239 --> 00:13:03.520
for your results to be consistent, there are ways to do that. There are tools like virtual machines

00:13:04.159 --> 00:13:09.200
and Docker, which are popular in the cloud space for reproducing system environments.

00:13:10.239 --> 00:13:15.520
And there's also a system there, Nix, which is built to, again, reproduce a system environment.

00:13:16.239 --> 00:13:20.640
But Nix is really interesting because it's sort of you build your environment using code.

00:13:21.359 --> 00:13:28.559
And then because of the way Nix works, it can use cryptographic hashes to actually confirm

00:13:28.559 --> 00:13:33.280
to yourself that you really do have the same version of a certain piece of source code as

00:13:33.280 --> 00:13:39.919
somebody else running Nix. It's a very exact way of making sure that your source code and

00:13:39.919 --> 00:13:48.159
environments match. But there are downsides. Anyone who's built the Tidyverse from scratch

00:13:48.159 --> 00:13:55.679
will know that building tools from source, if there are many of them, can take a very long time.

00:13:55.679 --> 00:13:58.880
And the more you have to build from source and the more you have to reproduce in your environment,

00:13:59.520 --> 00:14:02.880
the longer this will take, especially without things like binary caching.

00:14:03.679 --> 00:14:09.520
And the other downside is that this can be quite difficult to use, particularly very advanced

00:14:09.520 --> 00:14:15.840
tools like Nix can be hard to use if you haven't seen it before. And there is steep learning curves.

00:14:15.840 --> 00:14:21.840
Even with a fully reproducible environment from source code, there is one more level that I want

00:14:21.840 --> 00:14:28.159
to talk about. This one will affect you only very rarely. And that's that when you take a

00:14:28.159 --> 00:14:34.080
piece of source code and you compile it for a computer, it compiles it into a machine-specific

00:14:34.080 --> 00:14:42.640
language. So if you have something like a Windows desktop workstation or a Mac laptop

00:14:42.719 --> 00:14:47.760
and something like a phone, each of these things will run slightly different versions of machine

00:14:47.760 --> 00:14:52.719
language. And that means even if you have exactly the same source code, if you compile it for these

00:14:52.719 --> 00:15:00.239
different types of machines, you can get different answers. 99% of the time, this doesn't really

00:15:00.239 --> 00:15:06.479
affect you, but it can. It can happen. And here's an example of such a thing. Here's an R console.

00:15:06.479 --> 00:15:10.239
And what I've done here is I'm inverting a matrix essentially. And you'll see that if you look at

00:15:10.239 --> 00:15:14.799
the numbers in this example, they're reasonable numbers. They're not too big. They're not tiny.

00:15:14.799 --> 00:15:19.679
They're just sort of reasonably sized numbers. But in fact, this example, those numbers have

00:15:19.679 --> 00:15:24.320
been specially chosen to demonstrate this problem. In this case, there's two different operating

00:15:24.320 --> 00:15:30.880
systems running those consoles. And you'll see that on the left, the result ends in 3015.

00:15:30.880 --> 00:15:36.479
And on the right, it ends in 3046. And you do get slightly different answers with this example.

00:15:37.280 --> 00:15:41.200
The reason for this, by the way, is something called floating point determinism.

00:15:42.640 --> 00:15:47.599
So you can demonstrate this easier with this example. Basically, the problem comes down to

00:15:47.599 --> 00:15:52.479
the fact that when you're doing floating point computations on a computer, the order of operations

00:15:52.479 --> 00:15:58.080
matter. So when your source code is compiled into machine language, the exact order that the

00:15:58.080 --> 00:16:03.679
computer chooses to do things makes a very small difference to the answers. So here, I'm adding

00:16:03.679 --> 00:16:12.640
0.1 plus 0.2, and then 0.3. And I get an answer, 0.6 stuff. And here, I'm adding 0.2 plus 0.3,

00:16:12.640 --> 00:16:17.679
and then 0.1. And I get a slightly different answer. If you want to try this yourself in R,

00:16:17.679 --> 00:16:25.119
do make sure to turn on this option, which tells R to print more digits when it's answering results.

00:16:26.320 --> 00:16:31.919
So the important thing to note here is that really neither of these are perfectly exact.

00:16:31.919 --> 00:16:38.000
And no computer is perfectly exact when it's calculating floating point or non-integer

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:43.200
calculations. And the exact answer that you get can depend on the system you're running on,

00:16:43.200 --> 00:16:50.320
even if everything else is the same. There's some more information about that in my slides,

00:16:50.320 --> 00:16:54.159
if you do want to know more about that. I won't go into any more detail about this,

00:16:54.159 --> 00:17:00.320
other than to say that this effect exists. But I do want to just point out that even though

00:17:00.320 --> 00:17:06.800
these kinds of things are rare, they do happen. Here's an example in the NumPy GitHub repo,

00:17:06.800 --> 00:17:10.479
where someone asks, I'm calculating the hyperbolic tan of some function,

00:17:11.119 --> 00:17:15.599
of some number, and I get two different answers on Linux and Windows. And in this case, Linux is

00:17:15.599 --> 00:17:20.800
just that little bit more accurate. And they're asking, well, why is this? Is there anything that

00:17:20.800 --> 00:17:26.160
can be done? And one of the developers answers, in general, NumPy doesn't attempt to provide exactly

00:17:26.160 --> 00:17:31.359
the same results on different platforms. It's essentially impossible for floating point code.

00:17:32.479 --> 00:17:40.239
So if you really wanted to make your data analysis to the exact number reproducible anywhere,

00:17:41.199 --> 00:17:46.719
this is a problem. So we think, OK, well, is there a way that we can compile our software

00:17:46.719 --> 00:17:52.160
so that it's using the same machine language anywhere we take it? And the answer to that is

00:17:52.160 --> 00:17:59.599
yes. And that's what I'm going to talk about now, this idea of WebAssembly. And what WebAssembly is,

00:17:59.599 --> 00:18:05.199
is a portable binary code format. So what binary code format means here is the machine

00:18:05.199 --> 00:18:10.479
language I talked about. And what portable means is that it's the same machine language on any

00:18:10.479 --> 00:18:15.359
machine. And WebAssembly has really been designed so that if you compile something into WebAssembly

00:18:15.359 --> 00:18:20.800
language, it will run anywhere with a modern web browser. So even things like phones and tablets,

00:18:20.959 --> 00:18:27.199
Chromebooks, laptops, computers, they're all running the exact same machine language. And that really

00:18:27.199 --> 00:18:33.040
gives you very strong guarantees about the reproducibility of the results. WebAssembly

00:18:33.040 --> 00:18:39.280
enables high performance applications on web pages. It's not the first implementation of this

00:18:39.280 --> 00:18:45.359
idea of a portable binary code format. There is an older thing called Java, which is probably the most

00:18:45.359 --> 00:18:51.119
popular example. But where WebAssembly really shines is that it's designed to work in modern

00:18:51.119 --> 00:18:58.319
web browsers through modern JavaScript APIs. And because of that, it's designed to be secure by

00:18:58.319 --> 00:19:04.079
default. There are very strong limits on what a WebAssembly application can actually do on your

00:19:04.079 --> 00:19:09.680
machine. It's very strongly containerized and sandboxed inside your web browser. And web browsers

00:19:09.680 --> 00:19:13.599
are designed really to be very secure systems because obviously you don't want any random

00:19:13.599 --> 00:19:18.160
website to be able to see your bank details in another tab, for example. Because of that,

00:19:18.160 --> 00:19:23.839
WebAssembly gains all of these security benefits essentially for free through the browser.

00:19:23.839 --> 00:19:28.640
So I'm the lead developer of a project called WebR, which is a version of the R interpreter that's

00:19:28.640 --> 00:19:34.079
built for this WebAssembly system. And that allows you to execute R code directly inside your web

00:19:34.079 --> 00:19:39.359
browser. And importantly, without a supporting R server, which is traditionally how things like

00:19:39.359 --> 00:19:47.599
Shiny apps run. You can run WebR server-side too. I know there are some people who are running WebR

00:19:47.599 --> 00:19:52.479
in a node process so that they can run R code on servers they wouldn't otherwise have access to.

00:19:53.280 --> 00:19:58.640
But today I'm just going to be talking about R in the web browser. In addition to the interpreter,

00:19:58.640 --> 00:20:05.119
WebR includes a JavaScript and TypeScript library so that you can integrate with the R session

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:12.079
from JavaScript. So here's an example of something doing just that. It's a WebR

00:20:12.079 --> 00:20:18.640
demo application. And if you go to the URL shown on the screen in my slides, you'll see

00:20:18.640 --> 00:20:24.880
this webpage come up. And what this is, it's a version of the R interpreter running in your

00:20:24.880 --> 00:20:30.880
web browser. So you can actually go and use R on machines that don't have R installed or any

00:20:30.880 --> 00:20:37.680
packages installed. You can just go to this website and use R. If you've seen something

00:20:37.680 --> 00:20:43.680
like RStudio before, this will be very familiar. It's sort of this four-pane data science look

00:20:43.680 --> 00:20:50.079
where you have an editor, a console, and plots. And what I really like about this slide in particular,

00:20:50.079 --> 00:20:56.400
these are quarto slides. They're web-based. And because things on the web plug in together very

00:20:56.400 --> 00:21:03.040
easily, what you find is that this isn't actually an image. It's a real session I can interact with.

00:21:03.040 --> 00:21:07.680
So I can really interact with an R session directly inside my web browser through these slides.

00:21:07.680 --> 00:21:13.520
In the editor, I could type some R code. I could do some analysis. Let's plot a histogram. So we'll do

00:21:13.520 --> 00:21:22.800
RNorm 1000. I can produce images. I can save those to my local disk. And I can even upload data files

00:21:22.800 --> 00:21:30.479
into this sort of file browser view, analyze them using R script, and produce outputs.

00:21:31.119 --> 00:21:37.520
What's hopefully clear here is that the real entire cycle of basic data science is possible

00:21:37.520 --> 00:21:44.160
to do inside a web browser reproducibly without having to install any software in your machine.

00:21:45.040 --> 00:21:50.239
That's the real benefit of these web assembly systems, I think. One of the things we found

00:21:50.800 --> 00:21:56.719
very popular with WebR is using it in teaching situations, too. So you can imagine here,

00:21:56.719 --> 00:22:01.599
if I was some kind of educator and I had some R code I was showing, one of the really nice things

00:22:01.599 --> 00:22:08.640
about having R code directly in the slides like this is that if someone asked me, oh, what if we

00:22:08.640 --> 00:22:13.599
change something? Like if I just change this code to get a slightly different output, I can rerun

00:22:13.599 --> 00:22:20.800
that code and the output updates live. This is really great for educational uses, not just

00:22:20.800 --> 00:22:26.000
because you don't have to go to another window, open R studio, reproduce your image, and then come

00:22:26.000 --> 00:22:32.319
back. But also, this is kind of reproducible by default. You kind of get it for free in these

00:22:32.319 --> 00:22:38.160
slides because the fact that you're seeing that image at all means that your entire R script had

00:22:38.160 --> 00:22:44.560
to run and it had to produce that image. It's not a picture like a traditional slide with a graph

00:22:44.560 --> 00:22:51.920
image would be, but it's a real live execution of R code shown on the screen. So it has to be

00:22:51.920 --> 00:22:58.959
reproducible for this to actually show anything at all. And that takes me on to Shiny Live.

00:22:59.520 --> 00:23:06.079
So what this is, is a system for Shiny for R and Shiny for Python that allows you to run

00:23:06.079 --> 00:23:12.959
these reproducible applications in Shiny inside your web browser without the need for a computational

00:23:12.959 --> 00:23:20.479
server. So I'll spend the rest of the time in this talk showing you how Shiny Live works. And then I

00:23:20.479 --> 00:23:26.719
have some nice examples. So a traditional Shiny app looks like this. You will have some kind of

00:23:26.719 --> 00:23:33.359
server and then the people who visit your app are the clients and they'll open the app in their web

00:23:33.359 --> 00:23:38.959
browsers. The important thing to take from this slide is that Shiny runs on the server and in

00:23:38.959 --> 00:23:44.640
particular that means that your server has to be able to run R or Python code. Now that puts limits

00:23:44.640 --> 00:23:48.959
on the kind of servers that you can use to host your Shiny app. So if you're something like a

00:23:48.959 --> 00:23:54.719
researcher who's produced some kind of scientific output and you want to share that output with the

00:23:54.719 --> 00:24:01.040
world or with a reviewer, you're going to have to set up a Shiny server. And there are a few ways to

00:24:01.040 --> 00:24:07.760
do this. The simplest way is that when you run a Shiny app in something like RStudio, it runs a

00:24:07.760 --> 00:24:12.560
Shiny server in the background. And in that case, the client machine and the server machine are the

00:24:12.560 --> 00:24:17.920
same. But obviously that's not great once you actually want to distribute that app so that

00:24:17.920 --> 00:24:22.479
other people can view it. And in that case, you're going to start having to think about, okay, well

00:24:22.479 --> 00:24:27.680
now I have to manage some kind of Shiny server infrastructure. There are three ways to do this.

00:24:27.680 --> 00:24:35.119
There's an open source Shiny server and there's also a more paid for and enterprise ways to do

00:24:35.119 --> 00:24:43.280
this. So you might upload your Shiny app to shinyapps.io or if your institution has something

00:24:43.280 --> 00:24:49.119
like a Posit enterprise license, there are Posit tools and cloud tools that can make this

00:24:49.119 --> 00:24:54.880
easy to share Shiny app. However, if you don't have access to those enterprise tools

00:24:55.439 --> 00:25:01.280
and you have something like three or four projects on the go and you've produced three or four Shiny

00:25:01.280 --> 00:25:06.880
apps that you want to put somewhere on the internet to share, and you don't want to have

00:25:06.880 --> 00:25:14.000
to manage these over time, then none of these solutions are really a hundred percent great for

00:25:14.000 --> 00:25:18.000
you. I mean, shinyapps.io is pretty close. You can host Shiny apps for free, but there are

00:25:18.000 --> 00:25:21.839
computational limits and there are limits on the numbers of apps. So at some point,

00:25:22.800 --> 00:25:24.160
costs are going to be involved.

00:25:26.640 --> 00:25:32.719
One of the ways to get around this is that you could bundle your Shiny app and its source code

00:25:32.719 --> 00:25:39.839
and transfer that data to another machine. So you could send your data science output to someone

00:25:39.839 --> 00:25:47.359
and they run the Shiny app on their machine and they can view your output. Now that's useful for

00:25:47.359 --> 00:25:53.199
things like long-term archival or even something like peer review, where you're sending your app to

00:25:53.199 --> 00:25:59.119
a single other person or one or two other people to review. But the problem is it involves all of

00:25:59.119 --> 00:26:03.760
that reproducible workflow that I talked about in the first half of the talk. Now, all of those tools

00:26:04.800 --> 00:26:10.319
and methods to make sure that your output is reproducible needs to be taken care of by the

00:26:10.319 --> 00:26:15.839
person who's reviewing your Shiny app. And the problem is that the person viewing your Shiny

00:26:15.839 --> 00:26:20.479
app may not be a Shiny expert. They may not have used something like R or Python before.

00:26:21.520 --> 00:26:27.439
So if something goes wrong because of the lack of reproducibility, they're not going to know how to

00:26:27.439 --> 00:26:33.439
fix it necessarily. So the idea of Shiny Live is, wouldn't it be great if we could run these Shiny

00:26:33.439 --> 00:26:38.560
apps locally on our machine without having to use a server, but without having to install any extra

00:26:38.560 --> 00:26:45.920
software or manage this stack of reproducible software. The way it works is that when you have

00:26:45.920 --> 00:26:52.640
a Shiny Live app, the web server no longer has to run R or Python code. It just becomes a static

00:26:52.640 --> 00:26:59.920
web server. And that means it just serves files rather than running code. And then anyone who

00:26:59.920 --> 00:27:06.719
visits your Shiny app, Shiny itself loads on their machine locally inside the web browser.

00:27:07.439 --> 00:27:12.400
And in the case of Shiny Live through WebAssembly is able to run that Shiny app locally.

00:27:12.400 --> 00:27:20.400
One of the nice things about this too, is that serving static files is very efficient. Serving

00:27:20.400 --> 00:27:25.520
static files on the web has been around a long time and servers are very good at it. And that

00:27:25.520 --> 00:27:30.160
means that because that R or Python code is not running on that static web server, it's running

00:27:30.160 --> 00:27:35.680
on the client, the load associated with having many users is shared over each of those users'

00:27:35.680 --> 00:27:40.880
machines. So there's no chance of overloading something like a Shiny server if you have lots

00:27:40.880 --> 00:27:47.839
of users, because they all are running a local version of that computation to produce your data

00:27:47.839 --> 00:27:52.160
science output. There are lots of static web servers available. The one that people are probably

00:27:52.160 --> 00:27:58.319
most familiar with is GitHub Pages. You can serve static files for free on GitHub Pages,

00:27:59.040 --> 00:28:05.920
but there are others too, both paid and enterprise software is available to serve static files.

00:28:05.920 --> 00:28:13.280
And like I say, this is a very efficient thing to do. So that's why companies can provide static

00:28:13.280 --> 00:28:20.800
web services for free or for very cheap. When you load Shiny Live, there's a URL on the screen

00:28:20.800 --> 00:28:26.160
there if you want to try this out yourself. This is a Shiny Live editor, and it's actually running

00:28:26.160 --> 00:28:32.400
a live Shiny app in my web browser right now. So I can play with the slider and see reactive

00:28:32.400 --> 00:28:36.640
results. But one thing that's different between this and the traditional Shiny deployment is that

00:28:36.640 --> 00:28:42.959
I can edit the code. We found this really useful for teaching. In particular, if someone hasn't

00:28:42.959 --> 00:28:48.640
seen Shiny before, they don't have to install R, they don't have to install Python, they don't have

00:28:48.640 --> 00:28:53.119
to download the Shiny package. They can just go to this website and they get an editor and they can

00:28:53.119 --> 00:28:59.760
change the source code and see the results immediately. And we have done this. We've

00:28:59.760 --> 00:29:06.640
actually run an introduction to Shiny sessions where users have used the Shiny Live web browser

00:29:06.640 --> 00:29:11.119
for the first time learning Shiny, and they didn't feel like they needed to install

00:29:11.119 --> 00:29:15.920
the software. They were perfectly happy to learn the basics directly inside the web browser. So

00:29:15.920 --> 00:29:21.359
we find that, like I say, really, really useful for teaching. If you do use Shiny Live, one of the

00:29:21.359 --> 00:29:27.359
things you might want to do is embed a Shiny application inside a wider document. And as I

00:29:27.359 --> 00:29:34.000
said, these slides are quarter slides. Quarter can also produce long form documents. So you could

00:29:34.000 --> 00:29:42.160
write a data analysis describing the trial that you ran and describing what the data shows.

00:29:42.800 --> 00:29:48.719
And right in the middle of that, you can actually add a Shiny application directly into the source

00:29:48.719 --> 00:29:55.599
code of that document. If you do that, in this case, there's some slides. It gives you a slide

00:29:55.599 --> 00:30:01.280
with your Shiny app. And in the case of something like a website output on a quarter document,

00:30:01.280 --> 00:30:07.520
it will just drop that Shiny Live app directly inside your long form document, which is really

00:30:07.520 --> 00:30:14.079
nice for interactive demonstrations of outputs. You don't have to use quarter though. If you have

00:30:14.079 --> 00:30:19.520
a Shiny app that already exists, you can install the Shiny Live R package. And with one line of

00:30:19.520 --> 00:30:26.239
code, this will take your Shiny app and convert it into a Shiny Live app. What this does is give

00:30:26.239 --> 00:30:31.359
you a bundle of files that's ready to transfer to another machine or to host on a static web

00:30:31.359 --> 00:30:37.119
service like GitHub. If you are sending this to someone and you give them this bundle of files,

00:30:37.119 --> 00:30:42.319
in theory, all you need to do to run that Shiny app is to run a static web server. And there's

00:30:42.319 --> 00:30:47.920
various ways to do this. If you have R installed, there's a one-liner that will give you a static

00:30:47.920 --> 00:30:52.880
server. But even if you're using Shiny for R, the person at the other end doesn't need to

00:30:52.880 --> 00:30:59.599
have R installed if they have other ways of starting a server. There's a one-liner in Python

00:30:59.599 --> 00:31:06.880
and also in Node. Any way that you can start a static web server will work. It doesn't have to

00:31:06.880 --> 00:31:13.280
be within R. One of the questions I get asked is, what about packages? R has a very rich package

00:31:13.280 --> 00:31:20.079
ecosystem. One of the things we do for WebR is to compile as many of these packages as we can

00:31:20.079 --> 00:31:26.079
into WebAssembly. And we host a WebAssembly binary package repository at the URL there.

00:31:26.079 --> 00:31:32.239
Not all packages can be compiled for WebAssembly. There's a lot of restrictions in what you can do,

00:31:32.800 --> 00:31:38.719
particularly security restrictions. But we are compiling as many as we can. And so far,

00:31:38.719 --> 00:31:43.839
we have about 60% of CRAN packages available for WebR. So there's a good chance that

00:31:44.719 --> 00:31:50.000
if you use a bunch of packages in your data analysis, you'll either be able to load them

00:31:50.000 --> 00:31:55.439
directly from this repository, or you'll be able to find some other way to produce your result in

00:31:55.439 --> 00:32:01.359
WebAssembly. One of the things about R packages is that they update and change often. And despite

00:32:01.359 --> 00:32:09.760
our best efforts, if we want to do something like create a data analysis script or something like a

00:32:09.760 --> 00:32:14.640
Shiny app, when those packages change, I mean, how often have you gone away for a year, come back to

00:32:14.640 --> 00:32:18.640
some project, and then all of a sudden you update all your packages and it doesn't run anymore?

00:32:18.640 --> 00:32:22.880
It does happen despite our best efforts. And one of the changes we've made with the next version

00:32:22.880 --> 00:32:29.920
of Shiny live is that WebAssembly R packages will be frozen, downloaded, and bundled with your app

00:32:29.920 --> 00:32:35.359
automatically. So in the current version, when you load a Shiny app, it will go and

00:32:35.359 --> 00:32:40.560
download the latest versions of packages from the repository. However, in new versions,

00:32:40.560 --> 00:32:44.400
those packages will be frozen in time. And that means that your apps will continue to work

00:32:44.400 --> 00:32:49.760
indefinitely. As long as web browsers support WebAssembly, then they'll be able to load those

00:32:49.760 --> 00:32:54.400
packages because those packages will not change. They'll be fixed and frozen. This is obviously

00:32:54.400 --> 00:33:00.479
really good for reproducibility because the less things change, the more reproducible your result

00:33:00.479 --> 00:33:06.079
is going to be. So here's an example of exactly that. So if I just play this video, here is a

00:33:06.079 --> 00:33:12.719
Shiny app that loads the dplyr package. And what I wanted to really just show here is that when you

00:33:12.719 --> 00:33:17.439
export this to WebAssembly, you can see that each of those packages that dplyr depends on

00:33:18.400 --> 00:33:25.680
is being downloaded. So the dplyr packages and the Shiny packages will be downloaded at the time of

00:33:25.680 --> 00:33:31.439
producing your Shiny live app. And like I say, that means that they'll stay the same. They won't

00:33:31.439 --> 00:33:38.239
change. So here's the output of that exact app. And I have my filter based on dplyr. And if for

00:33:38.239 --> 00:33:43.839
whatever reason, that code that produces that filter was to change, it wouldn't matter. This

00:33:43.839 --> 00:33:49.920
app would continue to work because that version of the package is now fixed and part of the bundle

00:33:50.479 --> 00:33:55.280
for that Shiny live app. The R Consortium Submissions Working Group

00:33:56.640 --> 00:34:02.160
is an interesting application of all of these ideas. They're running a pilot at the moment

00:34:02.959 --> 00:34:10.639
based around producing Shiny apps in WebAssembly for clinical trial submissions to the FDA.

00:34:11.600 --> 00:34:15.520
So they're looking at the WebAssembly technology and the container technology,

00:34:15.520 --> 00:34:21.280
things like Docker and Podman, as ways of producing Shiny applications that are reproducible.

00:34:21.280 --> 00:34:28.479
So that if you're working in, say, the pharma space and you have some clinical trial output,

00:34:28.479 --> 00:34:34.239
you can send that output to the FDA in the form of a Shiny app that they can interact with. They

00:34:34.239 --> 00:34:40.800
can open it on their machine without having to install R and they can review that work.

00:34:40.800 --> 00:34:46.399
There's a good post on the Pharmaverse blog talking about the work they've been doing in

00:34:46.399 --> 00:34:52.879
this direction. So if you're interested in this, do go and read that. They're doing some really

00:34:52.879 --> 00:34:59.360
great work. Do bear in mind that not all R packages will work under WebAssembly. We are

00:34:59.360 --> 00:35:05.040
trying to compile as many as we can within the restrictions of the WebAssembly security sandbox,

00:35:06.399 --> 00:35:12.800
but work is ongoing here. If you do see a package that you use and isn't available in the WebR

00:35:12.800 --> 00:35:19.520
binary repository, do feel free to go and open a GitHub issue on the WebR repo, and we'll take a

00:35:19.520 --> 00:35:26.000
look at that when we can. Also, if you have your own R packages, custom R packages can be compiled

00:35:26.000 --> 00:35:30.959
into WebAssembly, and we're currently working on building GitHub actions to make this easier. So

00:35:31.520 --> 00:35:36.879
for your own package, you'll be able to attach a GitHub action so that when you release your

00:35:36.879 --> 00:35:42.239
package, it will go and build it into WebAssembly. The same kind of tools are also

00:35:42.239 --> 00:35:48.800
available on R Universe if you use R Universe. This is still experimental and we need to do

00:35:48.800 --> 00:35:54.399
some documentation updates and clarify some things, but as time goes on, this should hopefully

00:35:54.399 --> 00:36:00.479
become much easier and you'll be able to use your own R packages as part of a ShinyLive app.

00:36:00.479 --> 00:36:06.080
Also, bear in mind that the idea here is not that ShinyLive will replace a traditional Shiny

00:36:06.080 --> 00:36:11.280
deployment. There'll always be the cases where traditional Shiny servers are needed.

00:36:12.239 --> 00:36:17.199
One example that someone told me, which I thought was good, was that they use Shiny as a front end

00:36:17.199 --> 00:36:23.040
to submit jobs to high-performance computing clusters. Now, in that case, something like a

00:36:23.040 --> 00:36:30.000
laptop or a phone is not going to have the same kind of computational power as those Shiny

00:36:30.000 --> 00:36:35.439
servers. In those cases, a traditional Shiny deployment is always going to be required.

00:36:35.439 --> 00:36:40.879
Another reason you might need a traditional Shiny deployment is for browser security restrictions.

00:36:40.879 --> 00:36:46.159
Things like connecting to a database, for example, can't be done in ShinyLive at the moment

00:36:46.159 --> 00:36:50.800
because the web browser simply does not give you that level of access to the network.

00:36:51.679 --> 00:36:58.639
So if you have Shiny apps that do things like connect to a database and do some work on that

00:36:58.639 --> 00:37:03.360
data, in those cases, you'll want a more traditional Shiny app. And the biggest

00:37:03.360 --> 00:37:07.520
thing to bear in mind when you're building a ShinyLive app is that there are no secrets.

00:37:08.479 --> 00:37:14.800
Anytime you write some R code or you have some kind of data in your ShinyLive app,

00:37:15.360 --> 00:37:22.800
that is available to the client. Even if on a normal Shiny deployment, that data would not be

00:37:22.800 --> 00:37:29.120
sent to the client, with a ShinyLive deployment, everything is sent to the client. So no secrets

00:37:29.120 --> 00:37:33.439
or tokens should be in your source code when you write a ShinyLive app. That's really,

00:37:33.439 --> 00:37:39.040
really important. That's it. That's everything I want to talk about today. There's some links on

00:37:39.040 --> 00:37:44.479
the screen there if you want to learn more about WebR or ShinyLive. And do check it out on GitHub.

00:37:44.800 --> 00:37:58.639
And if you see any issues at all, just let us know through the issues tab. Thanks very much.

